Section 1.2: The Main Loop Deep Dive

The Glib GMainLoop in QEMU

```c
// softmmu/main-loop.c - simplified

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    // ... initialization ...
    
    // 1. Create the main loop
    GMainLoop *loop = g_main_loop_new(NULL, FALSE);
    
    // 2. Enter the main loop - never returns until shutdown
    qemu_main_loop();
    
    return 0;
}

void qemu_main_loop(void) {
    GMainLoop *loop = g_main_loop_get_default();
    
    // Main loop runs forever
    while (!qemu_shutdown_requested()) {
        // 1. Wait for events (with timeout)
        os_host_main_loop_wait(timeout);
        
        // 2. Process all events
        g_main_loop_run(loop);  // Actually does the polling
        
        // 3. Run vCPUs if possible
        if (cpu_can_run()) {
            qemu_cpu_kick_all();
            qemu_cpu_exec_all();
        }
        
        // 4. Check for migration
        if (migration_pending()) {
            migration_check();
        }
    }
}
```

The Event Loop in Action

```c
// The actual event wait function
int os_host_main_loop_wait(int64_t timeout) {
    GMainContext *context = g_main_context_default();
    GPollFD poll_fds[64];
    int nfds;
    
    // 1. Get all file descriptors to poll
    nfds = g_main_context_query(context, timeout, poll_fds, 64);
    
    // 2. Poll them (blocking call)
    int ret = g_poll(poll_fds, nfds, timeout);
    
    // 3. Dispatch ready callbacks
    if (ret > 0) {
        g_main_context_check(context, poll_fds, nfds);
        g_main_context_dispatch(context);
    }
    
    return ret;
}
```

What events trigger the main loop:

Event Type Example Handler
File descriptor readable VNC client sends key vnc_read_handler()
File descriptor writable QMP socket ready qmp_write_handler()
Timer expired VM timer timer_callback()
Bottom Half (BH) scheduled Device callback bh_callback()
Signal received SIGTERM signal_handler()

