Section 1.3: The Big QEMU Lock (BQL)

What It Protects

```c
// qemu_mutex_lock_iothread() / qemu_mutex_unlock_iothread()

// BQL protects:
// 1. All device emulation state
// 2. Guest memory access (except DMA)
// 3. I/O port operations (inb/outb)
// 4. MMIO operations
// 5. CPU state (except when running KVM)

// Example: Device MMIO handler - MUST hold BQL
static uint64_t my_mmio_read(void *opaque, hwaddr addr, unsigned size) {
    // BQL is held by the caller (main loop or vCPU)
    MyDevice *dev = opaque;
    return dev->registers[addr >> 2];
}
```

Why BQL Is a Bottleneck

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    BQL CONTENTION SCENARIO                      │
│                                                                 │
│  vCPU 1: Need to do MMIO → acquire BQL                         │
│  vCPU 2: Need to do MMIO → waiting for BQL                     │
│  vCPU 3: Need to do MMIO → waiting for BQL                     │
│  Main Thread: Processing VNC → waiting for BQL                │
│                                                                 │
│  Result: All I/O serialized through BQL!                       │
│  - 1 vCPU can do MMIO at a time                               │
│  - 100Gbps networking → BQL becomes bottleneck                │
│  - Solution: IOThreads (below)                                │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

When BQL Is Held vs Released

```c
// vCPU thread in KVM mode
static int kvm_cpu_exec(CPUState *cpu) {
    // 1. Release BQL before KVM_RUN (guest code runs without BQL)
    qemu_mutex_unlock_iothread();
    
    // 2. Run guest code in KVM
    int ret = kvm_vcpu_ioctl(cpu, KVM_RUN, 0);
    
    // 3. Re-acquire BQL after KVM_RUN (for device emulation)
    qemu_mutex_lock_iothread();
    
    // 4. Handle VM exits (MMIO, I/O, etc.)
    if (ret == KVM_EXIT_IO) {
        // BQL is held, safe to access devices
        handle_io_exit(cpu, exit);
    }
    
    return ret;
}
```

Principal Insight: The BQL is held only for the minimum time necessary. This is why QEMU can achieve near-native performance with KVM.

