Section 2.2: AioContext - The Per-Thread Event Loop

AioContext vs GMainLoop

```c
// include/block/aio.h

struct AioContext {
    GMainContext *gctx;        // Glib context (for file descriptors)
    
    // QEMU-specific event sources
    QEMUBHList *bh_list;       // Bottom Halves
    QEMUTimerList *timer_list; // Timers
    EventNotifier *notifiers;  // Event notifiers
    
    // Threading
    QemuMutex lock;
    QemuCond cond;
    bool walking;
};
```

Converting Legacy Code to AioContext

```c
// LEGACY (uses main loop implicitly)
qemu_aio_set_fd_handler(fd, read_cb, write_cb, opaque);

// MODERN (explicit AioContext)
AioContext *ctx = iothread_get_aio_context(iothread);
aio_set_fd_handler(ctx, fd, read_cb, write_cb, opaque);
```

Critical: Legacy APIs can crash or deadlock if called from an IOThread because they implicitly use the main loop's AioContext and assume BQL is held.

Bottom Halves (BH) in IOThreads

```c
// BH = deferred callback, like a tasklet
static void my_bh_callback(void *opaque) {
    // Runs in the IOThread context
    // No BQL held!
}

// Schedule BH in IOThread
AioContext *ctx = iothread_get_aio_context(iothread);
QEMUBH *bh = aio_bh_new(ctx, my_bh_callback, opaque);
aio_bh_schedule_oneshot(ctx, my_bh_callback, opaque);
```

