Section 2.3: Coroutines - Async I/O Without the Callback Hell

What Are Coroutines?

Stackful coroutines: Each coroutine has its own stack (like a thread, but lighter).

QEMU implementation: util/coroutine-ucontext.c uses makecontext()/swapcontext() for context switching.

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    COROUTINE EXECUTION                         │
│                                                                 │
│  Main Thread (BQL)                                             │
│      ↓                                                         │
│  qemu_coroutine_create(func) ─→ creates coroutine             │
│      ↓                                                         │
│  qemu_coroutine_enter(co) ─→ enters coroutine                │
│      ↓                                                         │
│  Coroutine func() {                                            │
│      // ... do some work ...                                  │
│      qemu_coroutine_yield(); ─→ suspend, return to main     │
│      // ... resume later ...                                  │
│  }                                                             │
│      ↓                                                         │
│  qemu_coroutine_enter(co) ─→ resume from yield               │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

Coroutine Use Case: Block I/O

```c
// Without coroutines (callback hell)
void submit_read(BlockDevice *bd, void *buf, size_t len) {
    bdrv_aio_read(bd->bs, offset, buf, len, 
                  read_complete_cb, opaque);
}

void read_complete_cb(void *opaque, int ret) {
    // Now need to continue from here...
    // But we've lost the original context!
    // Must chain another callback...
}

// With coroutines (clean sequential code)
void coroutine_fn read_block(void *opaque) {
    BlockDevice *bd = opaque;
    void *buf = ...;
    
    // This looks like blocking I/O...
    int ret = bdrv_co_preadv(bd->bs, offset, buf, len);
    
    // ...but it's actually async!
    // QEMU yielded the coroutine, and will resume it when I/O completes
    if (ret < 0) {
        // Handle error
    }
}
```

Coroutine Pool

```c
// util/coroutine.c
// Coroutines are pooled for performance

static QSLIST_HEAD(, Coroutine) coroutine_pool;
static unsigned int coroutine_pool_size;

Coroutine *qemu_coroutine_new(void) {
    Coroutine *co;
    
    // 1. Check pool
    if (!QSLIST_EMPTY(&coroutine_pool)) {
        co = QSLIST_FIRST(&coroutine_pool);
        QSLIST_REMOVE_HEAD(&coroutine_pool, pool_next);
        coroutine_pool_size--;
        return co;
    }
    
    // 2. Allocate new coroutine
    co = g_malloc(sizeof(Coroutine));
    co->stack = g_malloc(COROUTINE_STACK_SIZE);
    // ... setup context ...
    return co;
}
```

Performance: Pooled coroutines reuse stack memory, reducing allocation overhead.

