Section 4.2: vCPU Threads and BQL

KVM vCPU Lifecycle

```c
// accel/kvm/kvm-accel-ops.c

static int kvm_cpu_exec(CPUState *cpu) {
    // 1. Release BQL (guest can run freely)
    qemu_mutex_unlock_iothread();
    
    while (true) {
        // 2. Run guest in KVM
        run_ret = kvm_vcpu_ioctl(cpu, KVM_RUN, 0);
        
        // 3. Handle exit
        switch (exit_reason) {
        case KVM_EXIT_IO:
            // Re-acquire BQL for I/O
            qemu_mutex_lock_iothread();
            handle_io(cpu, exit);
            qemu_mutex_unlock_iothread();
            break;
            
        case KVM_EXIT_MMIO:
            // Re-acquire BQL for MMIO
            qemu_mutex_lock_iothread();
            handle_mmio(cpu, exit);
            qemu_mutex_unlock_iothread();
            break;
            
        case KVM_EXIT_SYSTEM_EVENT:
            // Reboot, shutdown, etc.
            qemu_mutex_lock_iothread();
            handle_system_event(cpu, exit);
            qemu_mutex_unlock_iothread();
            break;
        }
    }
    
    // 4. Re-acquire BQL before returning
    qemu_mutex_lock_iothread();
    return run_ret;
}
```

Principal Insight: The BQL Handoff

```
Time: ────────────────────────────────────────►

vCPU 1: [Run guest] [MMIO] [Run guest] [I/O] [Run guest]
         (no BQL)   (BQL)   (no BQL)   (BQL)  (no BQL)

vCPU 2: [Run guest] [Run guest] [I/O] [Run guest] [MMIO]
         (no BQL)   (no BQL)   (BQL)  (no BQL)   (BQL)

Main:    [VNC] [Monitor] [VNC] [Migration] [VNC]
         (BQL)  (BQL)    (BQL)   (BQL)      (BQL)

Key: BQL ownership switches rapidly → contention
     IOThreads avoid BQL entirely → parallel I/O
```

