Section 5.1: Beyond the BQL

The Scalability Problem

The Challenge: BQL serializes all device emulation. With 64 cores, 63 cores are waiting for BQL.

The Solution: Lockless device models.

```c
// Lockless virtio device (future)
typedef struct LocklessVirtIOBlock {
    VirtIODevice parent;
    
    // Per-queue locks (fine-grained)
    QemuMutex *queue_locks[VIRTIO_BLK_MAX_QUEUES];
    
    // No BQL needed for data path!
} LocklessVirtIOBlock;

// Multiple IOThreads can process different queues in parallel
static void lockless_blk_handle_output(VirtIODevice *vdev, 
                                        VirtQueue *vq) {
    // 1. Lock only this queue
    qemu_mutex_lock(&dev->queue_locks[vq->index]);
    
    // 2. Process descriptors
    // 3. Push to used ring
    
    // 4. Unlock queue
    qemu_mutex_unlock(&dev->queue_locks[vq->index]);
}
```

QEMU in the AI Era

NVIDIA GPUDirect + IOThreads:

```c
// AI workload: GPU memory access
static void gpu_handle_data(VirtIODevice *vdev, VirtQueue *vq) {
    // 1. Run in IOThread (no BQL!)
    VirtIOGPU *gpu = VIRTIO_GPU(vdev);
    
