PART 6: THE ULTIMATE DRILL

---

JUNIOR LEVEL (10 Questions)

Q1: What is the QEMU main loop?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

The main loop is QEMU's event-driven core (glib GMainLoop). It waits for events (file descriptors, timers, BHs) and dispatches callbacks. It also runs vCPUs and checks for migration.

</details>

Q2: What is the BQL (Big QEMU Lock)?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

BQL (qemu_mutex_iothread) is a global mutex that serializes access to device emulation state. It protects MMIO, I/O ports, and device state. All vCPU threads and the main thread contend for it.

</details>

Q3: What are IOThreads?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

IOThreads are separate event loop threads that handle I/O (block, network) without holding BQL. Created with -object iothread. Each has its own AioContext.

</details>

Q4: What is AioContext?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

AioContext is QEMU's per-thread event loop structure. It manages file descriptors, timers, and Bottom Halves for a specific thread (main loop or IOThread). Legacy APIs use main loop's AioContext implicitly.

</details>

Q5: What are coroutines in QEMU?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

Coroutines are stackful cooperative threads that yield when waiting for I/O. They make async I/O look like blocking code without callback hell. Implemented using makecontext()/swapcontext().

</details>

Q6: What is a Bottom Half (BH)?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

A BH is a deferred callback that runs in the next event loop iteration. Used to avoid recursion or to schedule work across threads. In IOThreads, BHs run without BQL.

</details>

Q7: Why does QEMU use glib's GMainLoop?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

Glib provides a portable, event-driven main loop with file descriptor monitoring, timers, and idle callbacks. QEMU layers AioContext on top for thread-local event loops.

</details>

Q8: What is the difference between main loop and IOThread?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

Main loop holds BQL and handles all device emulation. IOThreads don't hold BQL and only handle I/O. Main loop is a scalability bottleneck; IOThreads offload I/O for better scaling.

</details>

Q9: What are the three thread types in QEMU?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

1. Main thread: event loop + device emulation (holds BQL)
2. vCPU threads: one per guest CPU (KVM/TCG execution, hold BQL for MMIO only)
3. I/O threads: offload I/O processing (no BQL)

</details>

Q10: What happens in kvm_cpu_exec()?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

kvm_cpu_exec() releases BQL, calls KVM_RUN ioctl (guest runs), then re-acquires BQL on VM exit. It handles exits (I/O, MMIO, system events) with BQL held.

</details>

---

MID-LEVEL (10 Questions)

Q11: Why is BQL a scalability bottleneck?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

All vCPUs and main thread contend for one mutex. Only one thread can do device emulation at a time. With 64 cores, 63 cores wait for BQL. IOThreads avoid BQL for I/O, but MMIO still serializes.

</details>

Q12: How does an IOThread process block I/O?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

IOThread runs aio_poll() on its AioContext. When a virtio-blk device receives a request, it schedules a BH in the IOThread's AioContext. The IOThread processes the request, submits to host (via io_uring/AIO), and completes it in the same thread. No BQL needed.

</details>

Q13: What is AIO_WAIT_WHILE()?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

AIO_WAIT_WHILE() is a macro that waits for a condition while processing events in an AioContext. It's used in the block layer to wait for I/O completion without deadlocking. Must be called with the AioContext acquired.

</details>

Q14: How do you synchronize with an IOThread?

